'''James Oyedeji''' (June 1953<ref name="GSN">{{cite news| url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/breaking-news-ghanas-finest-football-historian-james-oyedeji-dies-at-age-63| title=Ghana's finest football historian James Oyedeji dies at age 63| work=Ghana Soccernet| date=6 April 2016| access-date=19 June 2016| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811070542/https://ghanasoccernet.com/breaking-news-ghanas-finest-football-historian-james-oyedeji-dies-at-age-63| archivedate=11 August 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref> – 4 May 2016),<ref name="Pulse">{{cite news|url= http://pulse.com.gh/sports/james-oyedeji-ghanaian-football-historian-dies-at-63-id4888414.html| title= Ghanaian football historian dies at 63| work=Pulse Ghana| date=6 April 2016| access-date=19 June 2016}}</ref> nicknamed '''Uncle Bode''' or '''Uncle Bodey''',<ref name="Goal">{{cite web|url= http://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/4389/ghanaian-football/2014/08/19/5044117/black-stars-3-3-real-madrid-ghanas-forgotten-football-match| title= Black Stars 3-3 Real Madrid: Ghana's 'forgotten' football match| work=Goal.com| date=19 August 2014| access-date=19 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="GSO">{{cite news|url= http://ghanasportsonline.com/index.php/local-football-news/item/8167-sad-veteran-ghanaian-football-historian-james-oyedeji-dead| title= SAD: Veteran Ghanaian football historian James Oyedeji dead| work=Ghana Sports Online| date=6 April 2016| access-date=19 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="SS">{{cite news| url= http://www.supersport.com/football/ghana/news/160412/James_Oyedeji_passes_on| title= James Oyedeji passes on| last=Al-Smith| first=Gary| work=[[SuperSport (South African TV channel)|SuperSport]]| date=12 April 2016| access-date=19 June 2016}}</ref> was a [[Ghanaian]] [[sports historian]], who was also the Chief Executive of the [[Tudu Mighty Jets]].

==Biography==
Oyedeji held a [[MSc]] economics degree.<ref name="MJO">{{cite news|url= http://www.myjoyonline.com/sports/2016/April-6th/james-oyedeji-dies-at-63.php| title= James Oyedeji dies at 63| work=Joy Sports| date=6 April 2016| access-date=19 June 2016}}</ref> He was primarily known as a [[sports historian]], being nicknamed "Uncle Bode" or "Uncle Bodey" due to his extensive knowledge of West African sport, in particular football and boxing.<ref name="GSN"/><ref name="Goal"/><ref name="GSO"/><ref name="SS"/><ref name="MJO"/> He also worked as the Chief Executive of the [[Tudu Mighty Jets]] and [[Okwawu United]].<ref name="GSN"/><ref name="GSO"/><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.sportscrusader.com/fa-must-concentrate-more-on-colts-development-james-oyediyie/| title= FA Must Concentrate More On Colts Development – James Oyedeji| last=Abacha| first=Saani| work=Sports Crusader| access-date=19 June 2016}}</ref>

==Death==
Oyedeji died aged 63 on 4 June 2016 at [[37 Military Hospital]] in [[Accra]] after suffering a stroke;<ref name="GSN"/><ref name="GSO"/> he had previously been admitted to the hospital in 2015 with a heart problem.<ref name="SS"/><ref>{{cite news| url=http://footballlive.ng/footballnews/world-news/celebrated-ghanaian-football-historian-james-oyedeji-recuperating-well-from-suspected-heart-failure/| title=Celebrated Ghanaian football historian James Oyedeji recuperating well from suspected heart failure| work=Football Live| date=18 February 2015| access-date=19 June 2016| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812125437/http://footballlive.ng/footballnews/world-news/celebrated-ghanaian-football-historian-james-oyedeji-recuperating-well-from-suspected-heart-failure/| archivedate=12 August 2016| df=dmy-all}}</ref> His death was marked with a one-week celebration.<ref name="SS"/>

