'''Wagon Works Ground''' is a [[cricket]] ground in [[Gloucester]], [[Gloucestershire]]. The ground was owned by the [[Gloucester Railway Carriage and Wagon Company]].
==History== The first recorded match on the ground was in 1923, when [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire]] played [[Lancashire County Cricket Club|Lancashire]] in the grounds first [[first-class cricket|first-class]] match. Gloucestershire played first-class matches at the ground from 1923 to 1992, playing a total of 155 first-class matches there, the last of which saw them play [[Somerset County Cricket Club|Somerset]] in the 1992 [[County Championship]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/493_f.html First-Class Matches played on Wagon Works Ground]</ref> One innings of note came in 1936, when [[Wally Hammond]] made 317 of Gloucestershire's 485 against [[Nottinghamshire County Cricket Club|Nottinghamshire]].<ref>[http://www.cricinfo.com/england/content/ground/57002.html#Profile Ground profile]</ref>
As well as hosting first-class cricket the ground has also hosted [[List-A cricket|List-A]] matches. The first List-A match held there came in the 1969 [[Player's County League]] when Gloucestershire played [[Yorkshire County Cricket Club|Yorkshire]]. From 1969 to 1992, Gloucestershire played 27 List-A matches there, the last of which saw them play Somerset in the 1992 [[Sunday League (cricket)|Sunday League]].<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/493_a.html List-A Matches played on Wagon Works Ground]</ref>
The ground has also played host to 6 matches involving the [[Gloucestershire County Cricket Club|Gloucestershire Second XI]] in the [[Second XI Championship]] and Second XI Trophy.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/493_sec.html Second XI Championship Matches played on Wagon Works Ground]</ref><ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Grounds/11/493_set.html Second XI Trophy Matches played on Wagon Works Ground]</ref>
The ground is still used for cricket today as well as [[association football|football]]. Following the rejection of Gloucestershire's plans to redevelop the [[County Ground, Bristol|County Ground]] in [[Bristol]], Gloucester City Council contacted Gloucestershire over a potential move back to the ground, which would see it redeveloped and become Gloucestershire's permanent home ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/county-cricket-2012/content/story/549003.html|title=Gloucestershire's future in doubt|date=11 January 2012|publisher=ESPNcricinfo|accessdate=15 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.stroudnewsandjournal.co.uk/sport/9484536.Light_supports_move_to_Wagon_Works/|title=Light supports move to Wagon Works|date=20 January 2012|work=[[Stroud News & Journal]]|publisher=www.stroudnewsandjournal.co.uk|accessdate=15 February 2012}}</ref>
